the simple fact that metastasis is not random.

540
00:31:46.556 --> 00:31:48.916
And I'm giving here an example of

541
00:31:50.176 --> 00:31:51.596
breast cancer metastasis,

542
00:31:52.416 --> 00:31:52.756
where we

543
00:31:54.016 --> 00:31:55.236
clearly know that

544
00:31:55.676 --> 00:31:59.656
breast cancer cells do not metastasize

545
00:31:59.676 --> 00:32:03.036
to all organs at the same rate, at the same frequency.

546
00:32:04.436 --> 00:32:06.516
So breast cancer cells show

547
00:32:06.996 --> 00:32:10.976
striking preference for metastasizing

548
00:32:11.096 --> 00:32:14.916
to the bones, lungs, brain, and liver, and this

549
00:32:14.936 --> 00:32:17.556
pattern is highly reproducible and predictable.

550
00:32:18.416 --> 00:32:21.696
So the question that I think we should be asking is

551
00:32:23.176 --> 00:32:27.116
why these organs? What is unique about the biology of these organs?

552
00:32:27.546 --> 00:32:31.076
And traditional explanations have actually

553
00:32:31.156 --> 00:32:34.756
focused on trying to understand mechanical factors,

554
00:32:34.956 --> 00:32:38.616
blood flow routes, vascular architecture, and physical trapping

555
00:32:38.956 --> 00:32:42.636
of circulating tumor cells. But mechanical factors alone cannot

556
00:32:42.696 --> 00:32:45.076
really explain organ selectivity.

557
00:32:46.276 --> 00:32:49.576
And really, metastatic success also requires that

558
00:32:49.616 --> 00:32:50.876
disseminated cells

559
00:32:52.096 --> 00:32:55.256
survive and grow in a specific soil.

560
00:32:56.746 --> 00:33:00.216
My lab is focused on studying metabolism, which is

561
00:33:00.296 --> 00:33:04.096
probably one of the most important things in the soil, in the organ that

562
00:33:05.736 --> 00:33:09.576
cancers metastasize. And why metabolism

563
00:33:09.636 --> 00:33:13.616
matters for organ preference? Well, first of all, it is really important for

564
00:33:13.656 --> 00:33:17.636
the arriving cells because they must be able to maintain

565
00:33:17.676 --> 00:33:21.395
their ATP production under different oxygen and nutrient conditions.

566
00:33:22.216 --> 00:33:26.016
It is also important for their biomass synthesis, for proliferation,

567
00:33:26.096 --> 00:33:28.706
especially when it comes to nucleotides and amino acids.

568
00:33:29.156 --> 00:33:31.876
They need to find ways to balance their redox,

569
00:33:32.656 --> 00:33:35.536
especially in oxidizing niches like the lung or

570
00:33:35.796 --> 00:33:37.216
brain. And

571
00:33:38.576 --> 00:33:42.476
they also need to be compatible with stromal and immune metabolism

572
00:33:42.836 --> 00:33:44.676
in the different metastatic organs.

573
00:33:46.856 --> 00:33:47.316
Equally,

574
00:33:49.316 --> 00:33:50.656
if not more important,

575
00:33:51.676 --> 00:33:55.596
though, on how permissive the

576
00:33:55.636 --> 00:33:57.556
organ of metastasis is going to be

577
00:33:58.516 --> 00:34:02.276
when it comes to metabolism, is what the metastatic organ provides or

578
00:34:02.316 --> 00:34:06.176
restricts. And characteristic examples are

579
00:34:06.356 --> 00:34:09.877
the brain, where there is low lipid availability, low serine,

580
00:34:11.596 --> 00:34:14.536
and also the constraints of the blood-brain barrier.

581
00:34:15.357 --> 00:34:18.937
In liver, we know that there is hypoxic and glycolytic

582
00:34:18.996 --> 00:34:20.236
adaptation pressures.

583
00:34:21.676 --> 00:34:24.976
There are very nice examples indicating that extracellular

584
00:34:25.055 --> 00:34:28.917
pyruvate in the lung and the oxidative environment can

585
00:34:28.996 --> 00:34:32.556
favor serine pathway use. And last but not least,

586
00:34:32.917 --> 00:34:36.897
there are site-specific responses to amino acid depletion and stromal support

587
00:34:36.917 --> 00:34:37.736
in the bone.

588
00:34:42.616 --> 00:34:46.397
So there are numerous examples emerging in the

589
00:34:46.457 --> 00:34:50.076
literature showing how metastatic cancer cells require their

590
00:34:50.116 --> 00:34:50.897
metabolism

591
00:34:51.877 --> 00:34:55.496
for successful dissemination to specific metastatic organs, and

592
00:34:55.676 --> 00:34:58.716
that creates novel dependencies, and that creates novel

593
00:34:58.756 --> 00:35:00.116
vulnerabilities.

594
00:35:00.996 --> 00:35:04.876
And I'm showing here a characteristic example from Matt Vander Heiden's

595
00:35:04.956 --> 00:35:05.236
lab,

596
00:35:06.296 --> 00:35:09.956
who has previously shown that HER2 positive breast cancer

597
00:35:10.556 --> 00:35:14.356
brain mets, unlike extracranial tumors, adapt to the

598
00:35:14.376 --> 00:35:18.196
brain's lipid-poor environment by upregulating fatty

599
00:35:18.236 --> 00:35:20.956
acid synthesis and desaturation.

600
00:35:20.976 --> 00:35:24.676
And as a result, this creates a novel vulnerability to inhibition of FASN,

601
00:35:25.156 --> 00:35:28.596
revealing a site-specific targetable metabolic

602
00:35:28.636 --> 00:35:30.316
dependency.

603
00:35:32.996 --> 00:35:36.976
Another example is a beautiful work coming from Sarah

604
00:35:37.016 --> 00:35:40.536
Maria Fenn's lab that has shown that breast cancer

605
00:35:40.596 --> 00:35:43.996
cells from lung mets this time rely on

606
00:35:44.016 --> 00:35:47.916
pyruvate to drive collagen-based remodeling of the extracellular

607
00:35:47.996 --> 00:35:51.776
matrix. So they are heavily dependent on this enzyme, pyruvate

608
00:35:52.056 --> 00:35:52.936
carboxylase.

609
00:35:54.016 --> 00:35:57.596
And not only that, but breast cancer cells from lung mets depend on

610
00:35:57.676 --> 00:36:01.296
MCT-dependent import of pyruvate and also

611
00:36:01.916 --> 00:36:05.576
serine biosynthesis-derived alpha-ketoglutarate to maintain mTOR

612
00:36:05.586 --> 00:36:06.636
signaling and

613
00:36:07.556 --> 00:36:09.716
sensitivity to an mTOR inhibitor,

614
00:36:09.856 --> 00:36:13.792
rapamycin.So the pattern is consistent.

615
00:36:14.512 --> 00:36:18.092
Metastatic success is not about brute force.

616
00:36:18.732 --> 00:36:22.092
It is all the growth signaling nutrient requirements that are

617
00:36:22.152 --> 00:36:25.612
markedly different in the different metastatic niches,

618
00:36:26.932 --> 00:36:30.372
when they are compared to the primary site, that can really

619
00:36:30.412 --> 00:36:34.092
determine targetable metabolic vulnerabilities.

620
00:36:36.272 --> 00:36:39.052
More recent work emerging from

621
00:36:40.572 --> 00:36:44.032
Van der Heijden and other colleagues indicates that

622
00:36:44.632 --> 00:36:47.812
no single nutrient explains all metastatic

623
00:36:48.552 --> 00:36:52.532
sites or organotropism. And what was rather surprising from

624
00:36:52.592 --> 00:36:56.472
this work is that depleting serine and glycine in vivo

625
00:36:56.512 --> 00:36:58.441
reduced metastasis in

626
00:36:59.312 --> 00:37:02.752
many sites, including bone, kidney, and ovary, but not

627
00:37:02.792 --> 00:37:05.132
uniformly in brain, liver, or lung.

628
00:37:06.992 --> 00:37:10.772
Equally, when it comes to asparagine synthetase

629
00:37:10.812 --> 00:37:14.652
dependency, this varied a lot cell line by cell line and

630
00:37:14.692 --> 00:37:18.192
also metastatic site. Of course, there were a few more

631
00:37:18.212 --> 00:37:19.112
generalizable

632
00:37:20.712 --> 00:37:24.212
observations from this work, and the ones that are

633
00:37:24.512 --> 00:37:26.252
worth noting are that

634
00:37:27.612 --> 00:37:28.652
there seems to be,

635
00:37:29.732 --> 00:37:33.292
across all metastatic sites, a marked dependency on de novo

636
00:37:33.372 --> 00:37:37.252
pyrimidine and purine biosynthesis associated with DH

637
00:37:37.292 --> 00:37:41.132
or DH and GART inhibition. And purine synthesis,

638
00:37:42.412 --> 00:37:46.032
in particular, emerges a broad requirement for metastatic growth

639
00:37:46.692 --> 00:37:49.852
independent of tissue nucleotide abundance alone.

640
00:37:52.812 --> 00:37:56.672
We were quite keen to address computationally whether the

641
00:37:56.732 --> 00:38:00.412
transcriptomic and the metabolomic signatures of the primary tumor

642
00:38:00.812 --> 00:38:02.612
can actually tell us something about

643
00:38:04.812 --> 00:38:08.752
both whether how metastatic the tumor is likely going to be, but

644
00:38:08.772 --> 00:38:10.712
also what is the site of metastasis.

645
00:38:11.692 --> 00:38:14.552
And in order to do that, we used a few data sets,

646
00:38:15.492 --> 00:38:19.372
like the MetMap data set, comprising of more than 500 cell lines

647
00:38:19.412 --> 00:38:23.132
with known metastatic index, and first selected

648
00:38:23.272 --> 00:38:27.032
the transcriptional and metabolic features that more

649
00:38:27.112 --> 00:38:30.252
strongly associate with metastatic index.

650
00:38:30.292 --> 00:38:33.752
When we applied machine learning algorithms to predict how

651
00:38:33.772 --> 00:38:37.692
metastatic or non-metastatic new cells are

652
00:38:37.712 --> 00:38:41.472
going to be, that were not included in the training set, we

653
00:38:41.552 --> 00:38:45.512
observed that we can predict whether

654
00:38:45.572 --> 00:38:49.372
the cell line or a tumor is likely going to metastasis with quite a high

655
00:38:49.412 --> 00:38:53.352
accuracy, more than 85%, 86% to

656
00:38:53.372 --> 00:38:55.312
be exact, when we use all the features.

657
00:38:56.712 --> 00:38:58.592
And surprisingly, when we

658
00:38:59.972 --> 00:39:03.872
did this analysis only this time with the metabolic

659
00:39:03.892 --> 00:39:07.552
genes, the accuracy increased even further, further

660
00:39:07.612 --> 00:39:10.472
emphasizing how important metabolism is

661
00:39:10.572 --> 00:39:14.502
in determining metastatic

662
00:39:14.532 --> 00:39:15.942
potential. What was

663
00:39:16.812 --> 00:39:17.852
less, though,

664
00:39:18.992 --> 00:39:22.112
clear and more difficult to predict was the site

665
00:39:23.072 --> 00:39:26.932
at which those cells and tumors will likely metastasize

666
00:39:26.992 --> 00:39:30.712
based entirely on the transcriptomic and metabolomic signatures

667
00:39:30.752 --> 00:39:32.092
of the primary tumor.

668
00:39:34.872 --> 00:39:37.932
And I think part of the reason why this is the case is

669
00:39:38.772 --> 00:39:42.712
because there are very few matched

670
00:39:42.752 --> 00:39:46.672
primary and metastatic sites, especially when it comes

671
00:39:46.732 --> 00:39:48.152
to metabolomics.

672
00:39:49.852 --> 00:39:53.732
In fact, to try to be able to address this, we developed

673
00:39:54.412 --> 00:39:58.072
a new tool that hopefully will be available very soon, a

674
00:39:58.112 --> 00:40:02.052
platform called MetaboForm, that infers tumor

675
00:40:02.112 --> 00:40:04.312
metabolomes from transcriptomic signatures.

676
00:40:04.392 --> 00:40:08.351
This is using a combination of both machine and deep learning tools.

677
00:40:08.882 --> 00:40:12.612
And I'm showing here a representative example of a heat map of

678
00:40:13.412 --> 00:40:15.332
liver metabolomics

679
00:40:18.572 --> 00:40:21.982
compared to different metastatic sites to appreciate how

680
00:40:23.612 --> 00:40:27.552
marked the differences are, and this actually correlate strongly

681
00:40:27.612 --> 00:40:31.472
with some of the published metabolomics data sets in these tissue types.

682
00:40:32.951 --> 00:40:36.792
Another thing that is quite important, another important factor to consider when

683
00:40:36.832 --> 00:40:40.772
applying such tools to predict how certain tumors are going

684
00:40:40.812 --> 00:40:44.052
to behave is that tumors are actually metabolically

685
00:40:44.112 --> 00:40:45.012
heterogeneous.

686
00:40:46.232 --> 00:40:49.652
And I'm showing here a representative example of a breast cancer section

687
00:40:51.172 --> 00:40:55.132
following mass spec imaging analysis that we performed

688
00:40:56.352 --> 00:40:57.411
from work

689
00:40:58.212 --> 00:41:01.852
funded by the Rosetta Grants Challenge Project, where

690
00:41:01.932 --> 00:41:04.972
we profiled actually a large number of breast cancer tissues.

691
00:41:05.432 --> 00:41:09.212
And the mass spec imaging allowed us to really capture the

692
00:41:09.252 --> 00:41:11.151
metabolic heterogeneity within tumors.

693
00:41:12.212 --> 00:41:16.192
And I'm showing here a representative breast cancer section where every color

694
00:41:16.202 --> 00:41:20.072
represents a metabolically distinct subtype within that tumor, and you can

695
00:41:20.112 --> 00:41:24.032
clearly see that the tumor cells in the periphery of the

696
00:41:24.112 --> 00:41:27.972
tumor invading through the normal stroma indicated in blue

697
00:41:28.072 --> 00:41:31.612
here, has a very unique metabolic signature.

698
00:41:36.532 --> 00:41:40.512
We were quite keen to follow up some of these observations in

699
00:41:40.552 --> 00:41:44.092
the lab and made use of a model that was actually

700
00:41:44.102 --> 00:41:47.672
generated in Clare Isaacs lab at the ICR of

701
00:41:47.752 --> 00:41:50.032
organ-specific metastatic clones.

702
00:41:50.492 --> 00:41:53.012
This was derived from the

703
00:41:53.072 --> 00:41:56.632
MDA-MB-231 triple-negative cells, which were

704
00:41:56.692 --> 00:41:59.272
initially injected in the primary site.

705
00:42:00.532 --> 00:42:03.032
And they were selected in vivo.

706
00:42:03.352 --> 00:42:07.132
They waited for the cells to metastasize at

707
00:42:07.352 --> 00:42:10.692
different organs and then did an in vivo selection three times.

708
00:42:11.212 --> 00:42:15.112
We were rather struck to identify that when we harvest these cells and put

709
00:42:15.132 --> 00:42:18.392
them back into the same

710
00:42:19.012 --> 00:42:22.868
media conditions in vitro, they retainVery

711
00:42:22.968 --> 00:42:26.448
unique metabolic signatures, with the most apparent being the one

712
00:42:26.488 --> 00:42:27.868
coming from the bone,

713
00:42:28.888 --> 00:42:30.908
that you can clearly see here

714
00:42:31.748 --> 00:42:35.728
when we profile the transcriptomics and the metabolomics profiles of

715
00:42:35.788 --> 00:42:37.688
these cell lines.

716
00:42:39.328 --> 00:42:43.308
Integration of this data actually indicated that the pathway that shows the

717
00:42:43.368 --> 00:42:47.088
biggest difference is alanine, aspartate, and glutamate metabolism.

718
00:42:48.488 --> 00:42:50.848
And indeed, we were able to show that

719
00:42:51.968 --> 00:42:55.668
when it comes to glutamine-related genes, it

720
00:42:55.708 --> 00:42:59.388
shows marked differences between the bone and the other metastatic

721
00:42:59.448 --> 00:43:03.308
clones. And of course, glutamine is the most abundant amino acid in the cancer

722
00:43:03.328 --> 00:43:05.728
cells and is used for many different things.

723
00:43:06.808 --> 00:43:10.748
It is a carbon and a nitrogen donor for a lot of different

724
00:43:10.788 --> 00:43:14.588
things. So it's difficult to try to identify

725
00:43:14.668 --> 00:43:15.788
what specific role

726
00:43:17.108 --> 00:43:19.168
it is needed in the context of bone metastasis.

727
00:43:19.608 --> 00:43:23.588
But to substantiate some of these observations, we went on

728
00:43:23.708 --> 00:43:27.688
to further show that indeed, bone metastatic cancer cells are

729
00:43:27.748 --> 00:43:31.268
very sensitive to glutamine dependency when it

730
00:43:31.648 --> 00:43:35.548
comes to bioenergetics force analysis, and they are

731
00:43:35.568 --> 00:43:39.248
more sensitive to both glutamine deprivation and treatment with a glutamine

732
00:43:39.268 --> 00:43:42.808
antagonist, DRP 104. And this appears to be

733
00:43:42.828 --> 00:43:44.028
specific with glutamine.

734
00:43:45.308 --> 00:43:49.228
What I mean by that is that when you deprive actually cells of another substrate

735
00:43:49.308 --> 00:43:53.258
glucose, there is no preferential effect in the context of

736
00:43:53.328 --> 00:43:55.928
the bone when compared to the parental clones.

737
00:43:59.488 --> 00:44:02.128
Glutamine import is regulated through

738
00:44:03.228 --> 00:44:06.528
key enzymes, key transporters, SLC1A5,

739
00:44:06.688 --> 00:44:10.228
SLC38A12, and the export is

740
00:44:10.588 --> 00:44:14.568
regulated by SLC7A5. So we were quite keen to follow up

741
00:44:14.788 --> 00:44:18.708
and see if those show any differential expression or activity in the

742
00:44:18.728 --> 00:44:21.048
context of bone metastatic cancer cells.

743
00:44:21.458 --> 00:44:22.308
And so that indeed,

744
00:44:23.168 --> 00:44:26.028
the levels are higher, but

745
00:44:26.748 --> 00:44:30.628
inhibiting one of these transporter, at least, is

746
00:44:30.728 --> 00:44:34.608
really tricky. The cancer cells have the ability to

747
00:44:35.068 --> 00:44:35.908
adapt, and

748
00:44:38.168 --> 00:44:41.028
so inhibition with a relevant

749
00:44:41.968 --> 00:44:42.828
inhibitor of the

750
00:44:45.208 --> 00:44:48.108
transporter didn't really show any preferential activity.

751
00:44:49.008 --> 00:44:52.488
However, we were able to show, using stable isotope tracing

752
00:44:52.528 --> 00:44:56.468
analysis, that indeed bone metastatic cancer cells show higher

753
00:44:56.488 --> 00:45:00.128
glutamine uptake. And this was actually validated in another model

754
00:45:01.428 --> 00:45:05.228
generated in the 41 when comparing the bone

755
00:45:05.268 --> 00:45:08.568
metastatic versus the primary parental cells.

756
00:45:11.648 --> 00:45:14.628
One of the most important roles of glutamine is to

757
00:45:15.688 --> 00:45:19.528
form an alternative substrate for the TCA cycle

758
00:45:19.548 --> 00:45:19.948
through

759
00:45:20.828 --> 00:45:23.468
conversion to glutamate and then alpha-ketoglutarate.

760
00:45:23.908 --> 00:45:27.188
So we did some stable isotope tracing analysis

761
00:45:27.228 --> 00:45:30.268
to carbon label glutamine, and then follow

762
00:45:30.608 --> 00:45:33.048
the tracing

763
00:45:33.528 --> 00:45:37.078
patterns of some of the downstream metabolites,

764
00:45:37.448 --> 00:45:41.188
and were able to show that the flux of glutamine to the TCA

765
00:45:41.268 --> 00:45:44.608
cycle is indeed higher as determined by

766
00:45:45.128 --> 00:45:48.708
M+4 labeling of some of the key TCA

767
00:45:48.808 --> 00:45:49.408
substrates.

768
00:45:53.048 --> 00:45:56.548
And then went on to show if there is any differential effect on

769
00:45:56.768 --> 00:46:00.288
GLS1 specifically, which is the key enzyme converting

770
00:46:00.968 --> 00:46:04.868
glutamine to glutamate. And saw that while there are no changes

771
00:46:04.948 --> 00:46:08.528
in protein or mRNA expression, there is a marked increase in the

772
00:46:08.588 --> 00:46:12.228
activity of GLS1, which again, was validated

773
00:46:12.248 --> 00:46:15.968
across different models. And that makes

774
00:46:15.988 --> 00:46:19.408
cells vulnerable to both inhibition

775
00:46:19.488 --> 00:46:22.108
of GLS1 with a

776
00:46:22.168 --> 00:46:25.028
CBA39 inhibitor

777
00:46:26.128 --> 00:46:27.628
across both models.

778
00:46:29.928 --> 00:46:33.638
So targeting GLS1 actually reduces

779
00:46:33.648 --> 00:46:37.388
proliferation and invasion capacity of

780
00:46:37.668 --> 00:46:39.448
bone metastatic cells.

781
00:46:41.008 --> 00:46:42.787
And we are in the process of

782
00:46:44.088 --> 00:46:46.648
trying to do this now in vivo.

783
00:46:47.568 --> 00:46:51.468
But the take-home message that I was hoping to finish with

784
00:46:51.548 --> 00:46:55.268
is that metastatic organotropism can be viewed as

785
00:46:55.628 --> 00:46:59.328
a sort of a metabolic coding problem, that different

786
00:46:59.648 --> 00:47:02.128
organs reward different metabolic solutions.

787
00:47:02.618 --> 00:47:06.368
And I hope I have convinced you that an integrated pipeline combining

788
00:47:06.728 --> 00:47:09.848
all this omics analysis, computation, and clone-based

789
00:47:10.468 --> 00:47:14.068
functional interrogation offers a practical route

790
00:47:14.148 --> 00:47:18.028
to identify organotropic liabilities in metastatic breast

791
00:47:18.088 --> 00:47:21.728
cancer. And with that, I would like to thank you for your kind

792
00:47:21.788 --> 00:47:22.508
attention.

793
00:47:23.908 --> 00:47:25.488
Particularly, I would like to thank

794
00:47:26.668 --> 00:47:27.848
Jessica and

795
00:47:28.788 --> 00:47:32.528
Theo, who did most of this work, as well as all our funders for their

796
00:47:32.568 --> 00:47:36.328
support and all our collaborators, without whom we wouldn't be able to do

797
00:47:36.368 --> 00:47:40.047
that. Thank you, and we'll be happy to take any questions.

798
00:47:48.368 --> 00:47:52.288
Great talk. As a kidney cancer biologist, I'm always

